Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313
New classiﬁcation of the distal attachment of the ﬁbularis brevis — Anatomical variations and potential clinical implications

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > Łukasz Olewnika,*, Michał Podgórskib, Kacper Ruzika, Michał Polgujc, Mirosław Topola > A R T I C L E I N F O > Fibularis brevis muscle Fibularis brevis tendon Fibularis digiti quinti Lateral compartment Fibularis muscle Anatomical variations > A B S T R A C T
Background: Although the lateral compartment of the leg is characterized by a high degree of morphological variation, very little information exists on the morphological variability of the ﬁbularis brevis muscle (FBM) and ﬁbularis digiti quinti (FDQ).
The main aim of the study was to characterize the morphology of the FBM tendon and its accessory bands, to classify them and to determine the incidence of FDQ.
The work attempts to determine the relationship between the types of the insertion of the FBM tendon and the occurrence of FDQ.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > Łukasz Olewnika,*, Michał Podgórskib, Kacper Ruzika, Michał Polgujc, Mirosław Topola > A R T I C L E I N F O > Fibularis brevis muscle Fibularis brevis tendon Fibularis digiti quinti Lateral compartment Fibularis muscle Anatomical variations > A B S T R A C T
Methods: Classical anatomical dissection was performed on 102 lower limbs ﬁxed in 10% formalin solution.
The morphology of the insertion of the FBM and of the FDQ was evaluated.

Results: The FBM was present in all specimens.
Two types of insertion were observed, the most common being Type I (70.6%): a single distal attachment in which the tendon inserts into the tuberosity at the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone.
The second most common was Type II (29.4%); this group was divided into three subtypes (A–C).
The FDQ was present in 17.7% of specimens and always with Type I FBM.

Conclusion: Both the FBM tendon and FDQ present signiﬁcant morphological variation.
Two main types of the FBM tendon determine the presence of the FDQ.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 1. Introduction
The lateral compartment of the leg contains two muscles: the ﬁbularis brevis muscle (FBM) and ﬁbularis longus muscle (FLM).
The FBM originates at the lower two-thirds of the lateral surface of the body of the ﬁbula, medial to the FLM, and from the intermuscular septa, which separates it from the adjacent muscles on the anterior and posterior compartment of the leg [1].
The ﬁbers of the muscle belly pass vertically downward until the muscle belly becomes the ﬁbularis brevis tendon (FBT).
The FBT runs with the ﬁbularis longus tendon (FLT) in a common synovial sheath behind the lateral malleolus, in a canal covered by the superior and inferior ﬁbular retinaculum [1].
The FBT then inserts into the tuberosity at the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone, on its lateral side [1].

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 1. Introduction
The ﬁbular muscles are characterized by various morphological variations, including the presence of accessory tendons or muscles, such as the ﬁbularis digiti quinti (FDQ), ﬁbularis tertius muscle and ﬁbularis quartus muscle [2–6].
The FDQ is a small muscle which originates as a small slip from the tendon of FBT to the extensor aponeurosis of the little toe, and is innervated by the superﬁcial ﬁbular nerve [5,7].
The occurrence of FDQ is usually asymptomatic; however, it can be associated with pain or compressive neuropathy [8,9].

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 1. Introduction
Fibularis muscle injury is frequently misdiagnosed.
FBT tears often present as instability and lateral ankle pain caused by mechanical or anatomical factors [10–13].
Tears and ruptures are commonly associated with other musculoskeletal disorders including tenosynovitis, chronic ankle instability and inversion ankle sprains, as well as ankle fractures [14].
The FBM plays an important role in the motor functions of the foot, assists in its ﬂexion and with the eversion (turning outward) of the inner portion of the foot.
Each of these movements helps to keep the body balanced when walking on uneven surfaces.
Therefore, knowledge of the potential morphological variability of this muscle seems to be key to forming a correct diagnosis and treatment.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 1. Introduction
Currently, relatively little is known about variations in FBT insertion and in presence of the FDQ.
A precise knowledge of the anatomical variations of the FBT insertion is required by orthopaedic surgeons (for reconstructive surgeries) and ts reserved.

In addition, the study also assesses the incidence of FDQ.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 2. Materials and methods
One hundred and two lower limbs (49 left and 53 right) were obtained from adult Caucasian cadavers ﬁxed in 10% formalin solution before examination.
The mean age “at death” of the cadavers was 62.6 years (35–86).
All were the property of the Department following donation to the university anatomy program.
To allow for complete identiﬁcation of tendon insertion, the inclusion criteria comprised sufﬁcient specimen quality and a lack of evidence of surgical intervention in the examined area.
Dissection of the lower limb was performed in accordance with a pre-established protocol [15–18].
Dissection started from the area of the leg, with the removal of the skin and superﬁcial fascia, and moved to the lateral compartment of the leg, thus allowing the fascia of the FLM to be visualized.
The FLM was carefully separated from the FBM.
Following this, the skin and subcutaneous tissue of

3.1.
Classiﬁcation of the ﬁbularis brevis tendon insertion

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
The FBT was present in all specimens.
Two key types, with subtypes, were distinguished based on the morphology of the FBT:

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
1 Type I — single distal attachment.
The tendon inserts into the tuberosity at the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone, on its lateral side.
This type was present in 72 cases (70.6%) — Fig. 1.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
Type II — bifurcated distal attachment.
The main tendon inserts to into the tuberosity at the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone, on its lateral side.
This type was observed in 30 lower limbs (29.4%).

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
Three subtypes were determined based on the site of attachment of the accessory band:

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
a Subtype a — the accessory band inserts to the dorsal surface of the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal.
At the attachment point, the FBT connects to part of the ﬁbularis tertius tendon.
This subtype was observed in 23 cases — Fig. 2a.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
b Subtype b — the accessory band splits into a medial and a lateral band.
The lateral band inserts to the dorsal surface of the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone, while the medial band (stronger) inserts to the middle part of the shaft of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone.
This type was present in ﬁve cases — Fig. 2b.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 3. Results
c Subtype c — the accessory band splits into a medial and a lateral band.
The lateral band inserts to the dorsal surface of the base of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone, while the medial band creates a fusion with the tertius ﬁbularis.
This fusion gives rise to the fourth interosseus dorsalis muscle.
This type was observed in two feet — Fig. 2c.

No signiﬁcant difference regarding the distribution of types was observed between sexes (p = 0.096) or body side (p = 0.341).

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 4. Classiﬁcation of the ﬁbularis digiti quanti tendon insertion
Fibularis digiti quanti was present in 18 feet (17.7%) of the 102 dissected lower limbs.
The FDQ was always present with Type I FBT.
Three types of FDQ were speciﬁed on the basis of distal attachment (Type 1–3).

a Type 1 — the FDQ inserts to the base of the proximal phalanx of the ﬁfth toe.
This subtype was present in eight cases — Fig. 3a.
b Type 2 — the FDQ inserts to the extensor aponeurosis of the ﬁfth toe.
This subtype was found in ﬁve cases — Fig. 3b.

c Type 3 — the FDQ fused to one of the extensor digitorum longus muscle tendons.
This subtype was present in ﬁve cases — Fig. 3c.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 5. Discussion
Morphological variations can be explained from an evolutionary perspective because over the course of generations, muscles such as the plantaris muscle or palmaris longus can become rudimentary [19–22], while others such as the ﬁbularis tetrius can overgrow [23].
Therefore, any morphological changes in origin or insertion may indicate that they have not yet reached the ﬁnal evolutionary stage [24], and the FBM has been found to have varied insertion types, and to display accessory bands [7,25–28].
Moreover, in some cases, an accessory band originates from the FBT and typically inserts to the proximal or middle phalanx of the little toe; this is associated with a tendency to develop the FDQ, a muscle present in monkeys [29].

The available literature shows only the possibility of additional bands originating from the FBT [7,25–28] or describes rare cases [27,30–32], and does not provide any uniform classiﬁcation of the varied forms of insertion of the FBT.
MacAlister reports that the FBT may give a slip tendon of origin to the abductor digiti minimi or may have a slip tendon joining the FLT [7].
Bhargava et al.
[27] describe the greatest range of possibilities for distal attachment of the tendon to the FBM; slip tendon inserted to the head of ﬁfth metatarsal bone, cuboid bone, calcaneum bone, fourth metatarsal bone, posterior tibio-ﬁbular ligament or middle and distal phalanx of little toe.

The third most common type was characterized by an additional band inserted into the extensor aponeurosis of the ﬁfth toe (n = 34 limbs).

Many anomalous ﬁbular tendons have been found to originate from the FBM or FLM and to have one or more distal attachments [7,25–27,31,33].
Unfortunately, the nomenclature applied to these anatomical variations is confusing, and often controversial; therefore, Sobel et al.
[34], propose that all such anomalous tendons should be referred to as “ﬁbularis quartus” tendons.
Due to potential errors in specifying the ﬁbular muscles/additional bands, we believe that our proposed classiﬁcation is an essential complement to current literature as it applies only to the morphology of the tendon of the FBM, and differentiates additional FBM bands from those associated with other structures, such as the FDQ.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 5. Discussion > Table 1
Another important aspect of the study was that it identiﬁes a relationship between the presence of the FDQ and Type I distal attachment of the FBT.
LeDouble [35] and Testut [36] speculate that absorption of the FDQ by the FBM and FLM would be a normal event and unavoidable considering the greater size and more constant FBM and FLM [2].
Although the prevalence of the FDQ is not precisely known, its occurrence varies from 15.5% to 59.7% depending on the study [5,7,27,37–40].
In the present study, its presence was observed in 17.7% of cases.
Percentage differences in occurrence are shown in Table 4.

Like other ﬁbular muscles, the FDQ is characterized by a variable distal attachment.
Its ﬁrst variants were probably described by MacAlister [7], who speciﬁed two types of insertion: a small slip tendon inserted to the extensor aponeurosis of the little toe and into the head of the ﬁfth metatarsal bone.
Two different classiﬁcations have been proposed by more recent studies [5,40].
The ﬁrst, by Jadhav et al.
[40], distinguishes ﬁve types of distal attachment: 1—on the dorsal digital expansion of ﬁfth toe (41%); 2—on extensor tendon (19%); 3—on base of the proximal phalanxof the ﬁfth toe (16%); 4—on the ﬁfth metatarsal head (21%); 5—dual insertion: on shaft of fourth metatarsal and head of the ﬁfth metatarsal (3%).
The second, by Demir et al.
[5], also consists of ﬁve types: 1—dorsolateral at base of ﬁfth metatarsal (27.2%); 2—dorsolateral ridge of ﬁfth metatarsal (18.1%); 3—dorsolateral of ﬁfth toe (36.3%); 4—lateral of extensor digitorum longus tendon — ﬁfth toe (9.2%); 5—lateral of extensor digitorum longus, dorsolateral of fourth metatarsal and dorsomedial of ﬁfth metatarsal (9.2%).

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 5. Discussion > Table 1
In both Jadhav et al.
[40] and Demir et al.
[5] as well as the current studies, the most common variant was found to be the distal attachment to the base of the proximal phalanx of the ﬁfth toe.
Interestingly, both Jadhav et al.
[40] and Demir et al.
[5] did not report any possibility of the FDQ being fused to one of the extensor hallucis longus muscle tendons, as noted in the present study.
In general, the occurrence of accessory muscles, including the FDQ, are asymptomatic; however, their presence can lead to clinical symptoms associated with compression of vessels, nerves and tendons.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 5. Discussion > Table 1
The FBM and FLT are play key roles in stabilising the ankle in the lateral direction, and splits or tears of either are associated with lateral ankle functional instability: a very common musculoskeletal injury; however, FBM tears are more common [10,41,42].
The tears are believed to be produced by awedgelike compressive forces by the FLT against the FBT in foot dorsiﬂexion [41].
Sobel et al.
observed FBT tears in cadaveric ankle in 37% of cases [10].
An important question in this regard is whether one of the proposed FBT types can inﬂuence the frequency of FBM tears.

Our study has some limitations.
Its main weakness is that the proposed classiﬁcation is quite heterogeneous, in that it is based on several morphological details, such as type of insertion or presence of accessory bands.
Nonetheless, this study helps raise awareness of “what to look for and where to ﬁnd it”, and offers a uniform classiﬁcation and terminology to act as a foundation for communication with surgeons.
Nevertheless, such a systematic classiﬁcation is needed to enhance the results of future procedures on the FBT and foot area.
Understanding the appropriate anatomical variants also seems necessary for proper understanding of the formation of lateral ankle instability.

Foot and Ankle Surgery 26 (2020) 308–313 > 6. Conclusion
Both the tendon of the FBM and the FDQ present high morphological variability.
However, the pattern of varations allowed to prepare an objectiﬁed classiﬁcation that can applied in further anatomical studies and clinical practice.
Knowledge of the appropriate types and places of insertion of the ﬁbularis brevis tendon can in future studies help to understand the stabilization of the lateral compartment of the ankle.
The occurrence of the FDQ tendon was always closely related to the presence of Type I FBT.
